              <span id="reviewTextContainer3924033555" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer15536596809099877425">Reading vlog: <a target='_blank' rel='noopener nofollow' href='https://youtu.be/1UrgtdFiGIo'>https://youtu.be/1UrgtdFiGIo</a><br/><a target='_blank' rel='noopener nofollow' href='https://youtu.be/zBOlVpBhVkI'>https://youtu.be/zBOlVpBhVkI</a><br/><br/>After reading Why I&apos;m No Longer Talking To White People About Race, last year, I wanted some literature that focused in more on the context of black femininism as that was one of the topics that really interested me. Bell Hooks&apos; Ain&apos;t I A Woman, seemed to fit that criteria perfectly. The title itself is taken from the speech Sojourner Truth made and is a fitting theme for the context of this book.<br/><br/>When I initially started readi</span>
  <span id="freeText15536596809099877425" style="display:none">Reading vlog: <a target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" href="https://youtu.be/1UrgtdFiGIo">https://youtu.be/1UrgtdFiGIo</a><br /><a target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" href="https://youtu.be/zBOlVpBhVkI">https://youtu.be/zBOlVpBhVkI</a><br /><br />After reading Why I'm No Longer Talking To White People About Race, last year, I wanted some literature that focused in more on the context of black femininism as that was one of the topics that really interested me. Bell Hooks' Ain't I A Woman, seemed to fit that criteria perfectly. The title itself is taken from the speech Sojourner Truth made and is a fitting theme for the context of this book.<br /><br />When I initially started reading, I felt so out of my depth at all I had to learn, which is quite frankly an embarrassing admission, because this is my history. I should already know this, but as I became more absorbed, I discovered an almost feverish thirst to know more. I found I soaked a lot of the content in early mornings before work and of an evening, when all was quiet, I had no distractions, and I could just spend ages and ages learning.<br /><br />I was shocked, appaled, disgusted at how slaves have been treated, how black women had to choose between fighting against sexism or racism, and how that caused more rifts and hatred within the black community and the community of women.<br /><br />As well as conversation on slavery, this book dissected some really interesting topics that showed that women felt that they couldn't become truly liberated from sexism because they didn't want to hinder the progress of equality for their race, yet that equality that most were unwittingly striving for was still feeding into the patriarchy that the dominant white race had set up. Yet to black people, this was still seen as an improved lot and a heap of people had been brainwashed to believe that being a strong, dominant woman had an demasulating effect on their men, so adopting that soft, feminine nature that they saw their white female counterparts displaying and succeeding at was what they strove for. They also seemed to want to be seen as submissive after all they had been through with slavery, doing hard labour for long hours and wanted to demasculine themselves.<br /><br />I also learned a lot about this matriarchal concept and how much that notion was actually a detrement to black womanhood. It took away the essence of the struggle <i> "and ignores the profound traumas the black woman must have experienced..." </i>.<br /><br />I did find there were a few things that became repeated, but it was honing into a specific point, so I feel like that was bound to occur.<br /><br />Overall, I learned a lot and enjoyed focusing more deeply into black women and feminism.<br /><br />Pick it up, give it a go and enjoy! &gt;(^_^)&lt; <br />Gén</span>
  <a data-text-id="15536596809099877425" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


