    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3529332243" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3529332243" />
    <a title="JJ ONeal" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/11662338-jj-oneal"><img alt="JJ ONeal" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1582666318p2/11662338.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3529332243?book_show_action=true">Feb 06, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="JJ ONeal" class="user" itemprop="url" name="JJ ONeal" href="/user/show/11662338-jj-oneal">JJ ONeal</a>
      </span>

          added it




        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3529332243" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer8957021052743331684">As I’m getting older, I appreciate how much of my education was biased by patriarchy and whiteness in general. No one pointed out the Civil Rights Movement was primarily a movement led by and for black men. No one mentioned the feminist movement was primarily a movement for white women. I was never taught about slavery from the perspective of female slaves or how stereotypes about black women would lead to years of oppression and terrorism.<br/><br/>To be honest, my heart feels heavy and disheartened. I g</span>
  <span id="freeText8957021052743331684" style="display:none">As I’m getting older, I appreciate how much of my education was biased by patriarchy and whiteness in general. No one pointed out the Civil Rights Movement was primarily a movement led by and for black men. No one mentioned the feminist movement was primarily a movement for white women. I was never taught about slavery from the perspective of female slaves or how stereotypes about black women would lead to years of oppression and terrorism.<br /><br />To be honest, my heart feels heavy and disheartened. I guess I shouldn’t expect that my grade school education would cover all this. I am a free-thinking person who has the agency and intelligence to seek out knowledge and different perspectives on my own. Isn’t that what we mean when allies for racial justice say “do the work”?<br /><br />Right now, it feels like my history classes failed me, my education failed me. My society is racist and sexist, and it always has been - even during some of our most celebrated moments like Civil Rights and women’s suffrage. I was ignorant of these nuances because of my own privilege. There are voices - like those of black women - who have a much harder time being heard. Hmmm, I don’t know how to review this book expect to just say please read it, it’s important.</span>
  <a data-text-id="8957021052743331684" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


